data.content:
Your assertions work but produce poor failure messages. MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions that tell you *exactly* what went wrong. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);                          // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));         // ✓ no built-in equivalent
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);                         // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users); // or:
    // var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(list)` | Failure says "collection was empty" vs just "expected True" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, list)` | Failure says "expected 3 items, found 5" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Failure says "value was null" |
| `list.Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle(list)` | Returns the element; fails with count info |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` line is fine — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" in MSTest, so `Assert.IsTrue` is appropriate there.
